00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:02.030
In preparation for today's reading,

00:03:02.030 --> 00:03:05.250
I asked the poets Aimee
Nezhukumatathil and Janine Joseph

00:03:05.250 --> 00:03:08.870
to tell me about the first
time they met each other.

00:03:08.870 --> 00:03:11.920
Neither could remember a
first or second time and

00:03:11.920 --> 00:03:16.230 position:56%
yet both claim they didn't
remember ever not knowing the other.

00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:19.270
Nezhukumatathil wrote,
"I feel I've known Janine

00:03:19.270 --> 00:03:21.800
since the formation of Kundiman.

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:25.750
Admittedly, my research
yielded no empirical evidence.

00:03:25.750 --> 00:03:29.060
But I think it illustrates
how writing friendships

00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:32.630
and writing communities, the
poems, stories and conversations

00:03:32.630 --> 00:03:36.110
that animate in arts
culture can be atmospheric,

00:03:36.110 --> 00:03:40.470 position:56%
a kind of weather system that
crosses boundaries of time and place

00:03:40.470 --> 00:03:44.720
to share experience that we feel
immediately perhaps intuitively

00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:49.130
in our bones before recognizing
as a fact like temperature."

00:03:49.130 --> 00:03:53.050
The fact is that Kundiman has
cultivated and nurtured a community

00:03:53.050 --> 00:03:56.940
of Asian-American writers since
its first retreat in 2004.

00:03:56.940 --> 00:03:59.600
And it continues to connect
Asian-American writers

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:03.100
across generations and aesthetics
through organized readings

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:06.320
like this one, publication
opportunities and formal

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:09.100
and informal mentoring
relationships.

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:11.640
You can find out more about
the specific accomplishments

00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:17.410
of our fellows, faculty and staff
at the website www.kundiman.org.

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:20.740
Today is all about
Aimee Nezhukumatathil,

00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:24.070
a two-time faculty member of the
[inaudible] and Janine Joseph,

00:04:24.070 --> 00:04:29.290
a fellow and a winner of the
2014 Kundiman Poetry Prize.

00:04:29.290 --> 00:04:32.160
If they themselves cannot
remember a first meeting,

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:36.230
their poems suggest an ongoing
conversation, that dynamically

00:04:36.230 --> 00:04:39.290
and persistently challenges
our conventional notions

00:04:39.290 --> 00:04:40.830
of everyday life.

00:04:40.830 --> 00:04:43.990
In poems of childhood
memory, town life, motherhood

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:48.840
and the deceptively ordinary,
Nezhukumatathil uncovers the animal

00:04:48.840 --> 00:04:52.060
and mythological, shining
a light on the strangeness

00:04:52.060 --> 00:04:55.390
of tilapia, high school in Ohio.

00:04:55.390 --> 00:04:58.980
Joseph's personal lyrics are
fraught with the political

00:04:58.980 --> 00:05:02.080
as she rewrites the
American dream as complicated

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:05.630
by her family's status as
undocumented immigrants.

00:05:05.630 --> 00:05:09.160
Hers is a poetics that attends
to these central fragmentation

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:13.150
of any narrative, formerly
rigorous yet riddled always

00:05:13.150 --> 00:05:16.220
with doubt of self and world.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:19.130
These two poets remind
us that writing the songs

00:05:19.130 --> 00:05:23.620
of one's self is neither a
[inaudible] nor lonely exercise

00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:27.210 position:56%
and that to sing it all is to reach
out to other people, other cultures,

00:05:27.210 --> 00:05:31.890
and histories, and other
possibilities of thought and being.

00:05:31.890 --> 00:05:35.700
Aimee Nezhukumatathil is
the poetry editor of Orion,

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:37.980
America's premier environmental
magazine

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:43.330
and the 2016-2017 Grisham Writer
in Residence at the University

00:05:43.330 --> 00:05:45.220
of Mississippi's MFA Program

00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:47.450
in Creative Writing in
Oxford, Mississippi.

00:05:47.450 --> 00:05:50.730
She is the author of three
books of poems, <i>Lucky Fish </i>,

00:05:50.730 --> 00:05:52.140
<i>At the Drive-In Volcano </i>,

00:05:52.140 --> 00:05:54.010
and <i>Miracle Fruit</i>
all from Tupelo Press.

00:05:54.010 --> 00:05:56.490
And her book of illustrated
nature essays,

00:05:56.490 --> 00:06:00.670
<i>World of Wonder </i>is forthcoming
from Milkweed Editions.

00:06:00.670 --> 00:06:02.990
Janine Joseph's first
book is <i>Driving</i>

00:06:02.990 --> 00:06:07.690
<i>Without a License </i>and it won
the 2014 Kundiman Poetry Prize

00:06:07.690 --> 00:06:11.290
and was published just this
spring from Alice James Books.

00:06:11.290 --> 00:06:14.100
She also writes for
opera and her libretti

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:17.420
for the Houston Grand Opera
include <i>What Wings They Were,</i>

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:19.780
<i>The Case of Emeline </i>,
<i>On This Muddy Water,</i>

00:06:19.780 --> 00:06:22.350
<i>Voices from the Houston Ship
Channel </i>and <i>From My Mother's</i>

00:06:22.350 --> 00:06:23.650
<i>Mother </i>.

00:06:23.650 --> 00:06:24.950
She's an Assistant
Professor of Creative Writing

00:06:24.950 --> 00:06:28.600
at Oklahoma State University
in Stillwater, Oklahoma.

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:32.510
Please join me in giving a very
warm welcome to tonight's poets.

